The shrine buildings once stood on the pagoda foundation platform of the Tagajō temple ruins, but in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567}} 40 ({{ill|lt=1965|Q2650|WD=Q2650}}), when the Tagajō temple ruins were designated a national {{ill|lt=Special Historic Site|Q26764449|WD=Q26764449}}, the shrine was {{ill|lt=relocated|Q2271023|WD=Q2271023}} to its current location. The shrine buildings were rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|WD=Q234510}} 13 ({{ill|lt=2001|Q1988|WD=Q1988}}).<ref>According to an explanatory sign erected beside the shrine by the shrine parish representatives.</ref>

At the Taga Shrine in Rokugatsuzaka, located almost directly north of the main hall of the Tagajō government complex, many bamboo hoops (taga) woven from bamboo—like those dedicated at the head shrine {{ill|lt=Taga Taisha|Q402091|WD=Q402091}}, which enshrines {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Izanagi|UNKNOWN}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Izanami|UNKNOWN}}—have been offered.<ref>According to Tōshirō Shimizu, “Tagajō Ruins,” in *Miyagi Prefecture Historic Sites, Scenic Places, and Natural Monuments Survey Report*, Vol. 3, Miyagi Prefecture Historic Sites, Scenic Places, and Natural Monuments Survey Committee, Shōwa 2 (1927), pp. 41–134, in the section “Legends of Various Places within Tagajō” (Kikuchi Mitsuya, pp. 128–131), it states: “Taga Shrine lies north of the inner fortress, beside the old Shiogama road. Villagers string together bamboo hoops equal in number to their age and hang them before the shrine to pray for longevity. Behind this small shrine, the foundation stones of the former shrine buildings are scattered, and several large stones excavated nearby are all massive. It is said that the former shrine buildings were grand and magnificent. The fields behind the shrine are said to be the sites of ancient halls, and even now they are cultivated without fertilization. In a corner of the temple ruins at Takasaki, on the pagoda platform, there is a Taga Shrine, but it was moved from here; before this shrine there are no hoop offerings, and villagers commonly refer to it as ‘Oise-sama.’”</ref> At present, the Tagajō City Board of Education officially recognizes this as the “Engishiki Shrine: Taga Shrine,” and has installed official markers and information boards. The former shrine site lies about 50 meters northeast of the current location, and through excavation surveys and environmental improvement projects in the Rokugatsuzaka area, the shrine was {{ill|lt=relocated|Q2271023|WD=Q2271023}} to its present site. Before relocation, a {{ill|lt=torii|Q234731|WD=Q234731}} gate was also in place, but it no longer exists. In the “An’ei Fudoki Shodashi” (An’ei 3 [1774]) of Ichikawa Village, only four shrines—the village tutelary Sōsha Myōjin Shrine (present-day {{ill|lt=Mutsu Sōsha Shrine|Q11658605|WD=Q11658605}}), Arahaba-ki Shrine, Hakusan Shrine, and Hachiman Shrine—are listed; this shrine is not mentioned, and details of its shrine traditions remain unknown.

=== Access ===
5 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Kokufu-Tagajō Station|Q898924|WD=Q898924}} on the {{ill|lt=Tohoku Main Line|Q681190|WD=Q681190}} of {{ill|lt=East Japan Railway Company|Q499071|WD=Q499071}} (JR East)

